Iratus Graiis quantum no- cuisset Achilles. The poet alludes to the Iliad of Homer, which he read at school with his preceptor, and with which the Roman youth began their studies—43. Bonae Athenae. “Kind Athens.” The epithet here applied to this celebrated city is peculiarly pleasing. The poet speaks of it in the language of fond and grateful recollection, for the benefits which he there received in the more elevated departments of inanimem—Artis.
